	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Summary evaluation of Fisheries Partnership Agreements</h1>

			
			<h4>
												05 July 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>As part of the preparation for CFP reform, the EC undertook an overall evaluation study of FPAs. Although the evaluation report is not publicly available, a summary has been published by the EC in its 2010 annual report on evaluations in the European Commission.</p><p>The overall evaluation study identified a number of trends, highlighting in particular the fact that the size of the European fleet making use of third-country EEZ (exclusive economic zone) access negotiated by the EC will probably fall: ‘This is particularly true of demersal fishing vessels, which now operate only under the four mixed agreements’, including the agreements with Mauritania and Guinea-Bissau. ‘The reduction of this fleet is likely to accelerate in the years ahead, largely as a result of the environmental issues raised by these vessels (overexploitation of stocks and environmental impact) and profitability problems’. On the other hand, fleets specialising in tuna are likely to remain at present levels. These tuna fleets are even looking at new opportunities for access to third-country EEZs. Fleets specialising in small pelagic species ‘have seen their fishing opportunities in the north-east Atlantic diminish and will therefore be seeking access to productive grounds’, such as Morocco or Mauritanian waters.</p><p>As far as third countries are concerned, the findings of the evaluation indicate that the partnership approach to implementing sector policy has given positive results. However, it is remarked that ‘the agreements also contribute to accentuating regional imbalances in an area where experience shows the best response is a transnational response … Fisheries agreements currently involve only 12% of the population in those ACP countries with coastlines’.</p><p>The recommendations of the evaluation report show that the issue of critical importance is the anticipated reduction in negotiated fishing opportunities, which will have the effect of ‘reducing the budgetary envelopes available for funding sector support to the point where they probably become insufficient to meet existing needs … One of the avenues to be explored in preparation for the reform could be that of separating the issue of access from that of sector support … the EC could negotiate with the third country concerned to establish a framework setting out the minimum conditions governing fishing operations in the EEZ, and leaving the majority of the financial costs involved in securing this access to European vessel operators. The sector support dimension would then be based on identifying the development needs of third countries in regard to their fishing sectors, with the option of providing support gradually as progress is achieved. This solution would have the merit of supplying the financial resources required to meet actual needs, and would probably motivate third countries that have not yet done so to enter into sector dialogue with the EC.</p><p>The evaluation also places emphasis on the need to find regional solutions: ‘it is clear that the external action taken by the EC will eventually benefit [sic] if it can rely on the support of competent regional organisations in addressing the common problems encountered by all coastal countries within a given geographic subgroup … There is also reason to hope that eventually these regional platforms can also become engaged in the management of fisheries agreements.’</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
EC, ‘Annual Evaluation Review 2009: Summary information on evaluations in the European Commission’, May 2010<br />
<a href="http://ec.europa.eu/dgs/secretariat_general/evaluation/docs/final_aer_2009_en.pdf" target="_self">http://ec.europa.eu/dgs/secretariat_general/evaluation/docs/final_aer_20...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>A key issue identified by the evaluation is the importance of motivating third countries, like ACP countries, to enter into or maintain a dialogue with the EC on sustainable fisheries. Indeed, if future agreements offer the possibility of better matching the financial resources made available by the EU with the actual needs of ACP coastal countries (through de-linking sectoral support from access), it would be a step in the right direction. An issue that still requires attention is how to gradually integrate these bilateral dialogues with a number of countries of a sub-region into a regional dynamic, focusing on issues of common concern, such as the fight against IUU fishing, the promotion of research, etc.</p>
		</div>
		
